article.description: Vince Carter scored 27 points and the New Jersey Nets continued their push for a playoff berth with a 110-80 rout at Cleveland on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Cavs drop 8 of last 12 games
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- Vince Carter and the New Jersey Nets are not looking back as they keep gaining on teams ahead of them. Carter scored 27 points and the Nets continued their push for a playoff berth with a 111-80 rout of the Cleveland Cavaliers on Tuesday night. "It was just a great effort from everybody," Carter said after shooting 11-for-18 to help the Nets bounce back from a one-point loss to Orlando on Saturday. "You've got to put the past behind you. All we can do is look forward and handle the task." LeBron James scored 24 points, but could not keep Cleveland from its eighth loss in 12 games. After the game, there was a broadcast report that general manager Jim Paxson soon would be fired. "I don't think it makes sense to comment on the truth or inaccuracy of rumors related to key positions in our organization," Cavaliers owner Dan Gilbert responded in a statement released by the team. Before that, James was obviously upset with Cleveland's worst home loss since a 35-point blowout by New York on March 20, 2001. "There's no reason we should be losing like this on our home court," James said after Cleveland dropped 27-11 at home this season. Nenad Krstic scored 18 points while Jason Kidd had 13 points and 12 assists for the Nets, who made a season-high 13 3-pointers and won for the ninth time in 12 games. The Nets shot 57 percent from the floor overall. "We shot the ball well, not only from the 3-point line but from everywhere," Carter said. New Jersey (36-39) moved within one game of Philadelphia for the eighth spot in the East. The Nets also are battling Orlando for a berth and must finish ahead of the Magic, who hold the edge in the tiebreaker by winning three of four from New Jersey this season. "We've always felt positive that if we can put a nice streak together we can make the playoffs," Kidd said. The Nets' third win in four games against the Cavaliers gave them the tiebreaker over fading Cleveland (38-35). The Cavaliers dropped to seventh, one game behind Indiana, which won at New York. Cleveland visits the Pacers on Wednesday night -- and could be without center Zydrunas Ilgauskas. Ilgauskas did not return after injuring his right ring finger with 7:03 to play in the third quarter. "He'll be held back and have his finger X-rayed," Cavaliers coach Brendan Malone said. "If he's good enough, he will fly in tomorrow to Indiana." James wasn't as sure. "It doesn't look too well for 'Z," he said. "It's going to be tough now." James finally got a rest after playing 278 of a possible 289 minutes over a 10-game span -- including two that went to overtime. He came out with eight minutes to play and New Jersey leading 92-71. New Jersey shot 13-for-23 on 3-pointers. Six Nets made 3s, including Jason Collins who banked in an off-balance shot with the shot clock about to expire for his first of the season -- putting the Nets ahead 82-59. "That's when you knew it was one of those nights," said Cavaliers forward Drew Gooden. "I played 19 minutes and didn't get a rebound so you know the ball was going through the hoop. "I sure kept inbounding it, though." Gooden scored 16 points on 8-for-11 shooting, but left with a sprained left shoulder with 1:47 to play in the third quarter. "It hurts a lot, but I'm playing in Indiana," he said. "It's a long season and I've had all sorts of injuries, some a lot worse than this." Gooden hit his first five shots, but got his third foul and went to the bench with 3:11 left in the first quarter. New Jersey promptly went on an 18-4 run to take a 34-25 lead. James then hit a 3-pointer, blocked a shot at the other end and made another 3 in a span of 40 seconds to make it 34-31. Carter quickly countered by making two of four consecutive 3-pointers by the Nets, who shot 6-for-9 from beyond the arc in the quarter to take a 58-40 lead at halftime.

Game notes
Gordon Gund was in attendance for the first time since selling 80 percent interest in the Cavaliers to Dan Gilbert for $375 million on March 1. Gund had been vacationing in China. ... Nets G Jacque Vaughn had surgery on his broken right foot and is out for the season. ... The Cavaliers team that went from a 2-19 start to a playoff berth in 1984-85 was honored at halftime. Roy Hinson, Johnny Davis, Mark West and Ben Poquette from that team were in attendance. ... The Nets are 25-12 when Krstic scores 10 or more points. ... Kidd's 12 assists give him 7,209 for his career, two shy of Lenny Wilkens for ninth place all-time. ... The Nets' four total free throws were a franchise low.
